I. Executive Summary

Project Title: The Circumnavigator: Design and Development of the First 3D-Printed, Autonomous Hemp Hydrofoil
Applicant: Hemp Nation One (Naval Division)
Objective: To design, prototype, and build a single-piece, sustainable hydrofoil vessel capable of autonomous, long-range maritime operation.

The Circumnavigator project is the fusion of sustainable architecture, deep tech autonomy, and next-generation naval engineering. We propose building a prototype hydrofoil with a monolithic, single-piece hull constructed from locally sourced Hemp Fiber Reinforced Polymer (HFRP) filament via large-scale 3D printing. This eliminates the structural weaknesses inherent in multi-panel construction, dramatically reduces manufacturing waste, and positions the vessel as the world's most sustainable high-speed naval platform.

The vessel will integrate state-of-the-art sensoring (Lidar, Sonar) and an AI-driven Real-Time Autopilot—the essential technological stack required for the validation goal: a fully autonomous circumnavigation testing its resilience, range, and environmental impact. This project attracts investment due to its low risk in material supply (locally sourced hemp) and high return in validated autonomous maritime technology.



II. Vessel Architecture & Sustainable Manufacturing

The physical design focuses on bio-composite integrity and hydrodynamic efficiency.

2.1 Monolithic Hemp Hull (The 3D Blueprint)

Material: Hemp Fiber Reinforced Polymer (HFRP) Composite Filament. Utilizing highly refined hemp bast fiber blended with a bio-epoxy or recyclable polymer matrix. This material is lightweight, strong, corrosion-resistant, and inherently sequestered carbon during the hemp lifecycle.
Architecture: The hull will be 3D-printed in one single, continuous piece. This revolutionary additive manufacturing approach ensures monolithic structural stability by eliminating seams, joints, and bonding points—the primary areas of failure in traditional composite boat manufacturing.
Foil Design: The hydrofoils themselves will be designed using NACA profiles optimized for high-speed water operation, fabricated from a high-modulus hemp-carbon composite for maximum rigidity and minimal drag. They will be actively controlled to maintain optimal height and stability in dynamic sea states.
Modular Infrastructure: The internal ballast, battery systems, and critical equipment are housed in modular, interchangeable pods. This allows for easy maintenance, rapid swapping of power sources, and adaptation for cargo or extended research payloads.

2.2 Propulsion and Energy

The Circumnavigator will be powered by a quiet, efficient Electric Propulsion System (dual submerged motors) optimized for the high efficiency afforded by the hydrofoil lift.
Energy Generation: A hybrid system combining a high-density, modular Battery Bank (e.g., solid-state or bio-battery technology) with Integrated Solar Panel Arrays on the deck and a retractable Hydro-Generator (Hemp-Composite Propeller) for energy recovery during transit.



III. Technology Stack for Global Autonomy

The core of the vessel's circumnavigation capability relies on redundant, advanced sensing and real-time decision-making systems.
